I have all the information needed. EAP-125 is a newly promoted AP (cited in engineering.md "Last updated 2026-04-28" as "New anti-pattern EAP-125") that lives in the engineering-anti-patterns doc but its content hasn't been indexed by the knowledge graph yet — it was just promoted. I have a complete picture of the architecture, the constants, the three view modes, and the failure modes. Now I can deliver the full diagnosis and fix.

---

## Diagnosis

There are **three distinct, compounding bugs** that all share the same root cause.

---

### Bug 1 — `linkColor` and `linkWidth` are not hover-aware in Pathway or Signal

In `ForceGraph.tsx`, the `linkColor` callback is constructed inside a `useCallback`. In **Mesh**, it correctly reads `hoveredNodeRef.current` and returns `LINK_COLOR_DIM` for unconnected links. In **Pathway** and **Signal** the callback was branched to handle semantic colors (Terra/Lumen, active/preview paths) — and those branches **exit before reaching the emphasis/dim logic**. The `hoveredNode` ref is never consulted in those arms.

```
linkColor(link):
  if (viewMode === "pathway")  →  return TERRA_LINK or LUMEN_LINK  ← hover never checked
  if (viewMode === "signal")   →  return SIGNAL_ACTIVE_LINK / PREVIEW …  ← hover never checked
  // only Mesh falls through to the emphasis/dim block
```

Same pattern in `linkWidth`.

### Bug 2 — `linkCanvasObject` (the overlay that draws the emphasis glow + core stroke) is Mesh-only

The `linkCanvasObject` callback — the `"after"` canvas overlay that draws the fat glow pass and the sharp core line on hover — has the same guard structure: it returns early for `pathway` and `signal` without painting anything. So even if `linkColor` were fixed, the two-layer emphasis visual (glow + core) would still be absent.

### Bug 3 — Particle emission ignores `hoveredNode` entirely

The wave-emission loop in `useEffect` calls `emitParticle` on all links that are on the active BFS path. It has no branch that checks `hoveredNodeRef.current`. When you hover a node, **every path link continues emitting** regardless of whether it touches the hovered node. The correct behavior: while a hover is active, suppress emission on links not connected to the hovered node.

---

## Root Cause

**EAP-125** — *View-mode branching that exits before applying the shared interaction layer.*

This is the anti-pattern promoted at ENG-266b / 2026-04-28. The general form: a callback that dispatches on `viewMode` at the top uses early-return for each view to handle view-specific styling, and then never reaches the component-level interaction code that sits below all the branches. Each new view added a branch that was self-contained — it handled its own resting appearance — but never wired back up to the hover emphasis model that Mesh had. The interaction layer is logically **orthogonal** to the view-mode layer but was structured as if it were **inside** it.

The sibling root cause on the particle side is the absence of a `hoveredNodeRef` check in the emission gate — the emission loop only asks "is this link on the active path?" and not "is this link connected to the hovered node?". These are independent state dimensions that were treated as the same question.

---

## Fix

The principle for the fix: **separate the two axes — view-mode color selection and hover emphasis — into two composable steps inside every per-link callback.** Step 1 picks the resting color for this view. Step 2 applies the universal emphasis/dim transformation on top. Neither step knows about the other. The particle loop gets a third gate.

### `src/components/ui/ForceGraph/ForceGraph.tsx`

#### Step 1 — Extract a pure resting-color helper (no hover knowledge)

Add this just above the component, next to `getLinkNodeId`:

```typescript
// ── Link resting color (view-mode only, hover-agnostic) ───────────────────
// Returns the "calm" color for a link given the current view mode and signal
// path membership. This function knows nothing about hover state — emphasis/dim
// is composed on top of this value by the callers.
function getLinkRestingColor(
  link: ForceGraphLink,
  viewMode: ForceGraphViewMode,
  activeLinkSet: Set<ForceGraphLink> | null,
  previewLinkSet: Set<ForceGraphLink> | null,
): string {
  if (viewMode === "pathway" || viewMode === "signal") {
    const isBi = link.bidirectional === true;

    if (viewMode === "signal") {
      if (activeLinkSet?.has(link))  return isBi ? SIGNAL_ACTIVE_LINK_BI  : SIGNAL_ACTIVE_LINK;
      if (previewLinkSet?.has(link)) return isBi ? SIGNAL_PREVIEW_LINK_BI : SIGNAL_PREVIEW_LINK;
      // Not on any signal path → render as resting Pathway color (dim directional)
      return isBi ? LUMEN_LINK : TERRA_LINK;
    }

    // pathway
    return isBi ? LUMEN_LINK : TERRA_LINK;
  }

  // mesh
  return LINK_COLOR;
}

// Emphasis glow color for a link — the wide, soft stroke drawn by
// linkCanvasObject.  Returns null when there is no hover active.
function getLinkEmphasisGlowColor(
  link: ForceGraphLink,
  viewMode: ForceGraphViewMode,
): string {
  if (viewMode === "pathway" || viewMode === "signal") {
    return link.bidirectional === true
      ? LUMEN_LINK_EMPHASIS_GLOW
      : TERRA_LINK_EMPHASIS_GLOW;
  }
  return `rgba(160, 160, 160, 0.18)`;
}

function getLinkEmphasisCoreColor(
  link: ForceGraphLink,
  viewMode: ForceGraphViewMode,
): string {
  if (viewMode === "pathway" || viewMode === "signal") {
    return link.bidirectional === true
      ? LUMEN_LINK_EMPHASIS_CORE
      : TERRA_LINK_EMPHASIS_CORE;
  }
  return `rgba(200, 200, 200, 0.9)`;
}
```

#### Step 2 — Rewrite `linkColor` as: resting color → then compose hover

Replace the entire existing `linkColor` `useCallback`:

```typescript
const linkColor = useCallback(
  (link: ForceGraphLink): string => {
    const hoveredId = hoveredNodeRef.current;

    // ── Hover emphasis / dim (universal across all view modes) ────────────
    if (hoveredId !== null) {
      const srcId = getLinkNodeId(link.source);
      const tgtId = getLinkNodeId(link.target);
      const isConnected = srcId === hoveredId || tgtId === hoveredId;

      if (!isConnected) return LINK_COLOR_DIM;

      // For connected links: use the resting color at full opacity — the
      // emphasis visual (glow + core) is handled by linkCanvasObject.
      return getLinkRestingColor(link, viewMode ?? "mesh", activeLinkSetRef.current, previewLinkSetRef.current);
    }

    // ── Resting state ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────
    return getLinkRestingColor(link, viewMode ?? "mesh", activeLinkSetRef.current, previewLinkSetRef.current);
  },
  // viewMode is stable per mount; activeLinkSetRef/previewLinkSetRef are refs.
  // hoveredNodeRef is a ref — deliberately NOT in deps so the callback identity
  // is stable (the kapsule re-reads it per frame via its own animation loop).
  [viewMode],
);
```

#### Step 3 — Rewrite `linkWidth` the same way

```typescript
const linkWidth = useCallback(
  (link: ForceGraphLink): number => {
    const hoveredId = hoveredNodeRef.current;

    if (hoveredId !== null) {
      const srcId = getLinkNodeId(link.source);
      const tgtId = getLinkNodeId(link.target);
      const isConnected = srcId === hoveredId || tgtId === hoveredId;

      if (!isConnected)  return LINK_WIDTH_DIM;
      return LINK_EMPHASIS_WIDTH; // glow pass width; core is drawn in linkCanvasObject
    }

    if (viewMode === "pathway" || viewMode === "signal") {
      const conf = link.confidence ?? 0.5;
      return Math.max(0.5, conf * 2.5);
    }

    return LINK_WIDTH;
  },
  [viewMode],
);
```

#### Step 4 — Rewrite `linkCanvasObject` to apply emphasis for ALL view modes

The existing implementation returns early for non-Mesh views. Replace it:

```typescript
const linkCanvasObject = useCallback(
  (link: ForceGraphLink, ctx: CanvasRenderingContext2D) => {
    const hoveredId = hoveredNodeRef.current;
    if (hoveredId === null) return; // no hover → library draws the link natively

    const srcId = getLinkNodeId(link.source);
    const tgtId = getLinkNodeId(link.target);
    const isConnected = srcId === hoveredId || tgtId === hoveredId;
    if (!isConnected) return; // dimmed links — nothing to overdraw

    const src = link.source as ForceGraphNode;
    const tgt = link.target as ForceGraphNode;
    if (src.x == null || src.y == null || tgt.x == null || tgt.y == null) return;

    const glowColor = getLinkEmphasisGlowColor(link, viewMode ?? "mesh");
    const coreColor = getLinkEmphasisCoreColor(link, viewMode ?? "mesh");

    // ── Glow pass (wide, soft) ────────────────────────────────────────────
    ctx.save();
    ctx.beginPath();
    ctx.moveTo(src.x, src.y);
    ctx.lineTo(tgt.x, tgt.y);
    ctx.strokeStyle = glowColor;
    ctx.lineWidth = LINK_EMPHASIS_WIDTH;
    ctx.lineCap = "round";
    ctx.stroke();

    // ── Core pass (narrow, sharp) ─────────────────────────────────────────
    ctx.beginPath();
    ctx.moveTo(src.x, src.y);
    ctx.lineTo(tgt.x, tgt.y);
    ctx.strokeStyle = coreColor;
    ctx.lineWidth = LINK_EMPHASIS_CORE_WIDTH;
    ctx.lineCap = "round";
    ctx.stroke();

    ctx.restore();
  },
  [viewMode],
);
```

#### Step 5 — Gate particle emission on hover connectivity

Find the `useEffect` that runs the wave-emission loop (it contains `WAVE_EMIT_INTERVAL_MS` and calls `emitParticle`). Inside the per-link emission gate, add a hover connectivity check:

```typescript
// ── existing loop structure, look for where emitParticle is called ────────
for (const link of pathLinks) {          // "pathLinks" = activeLinkSet or previewLinkSet
  // NEW: suppress emission on links that are not connected to the hovered node
  const hoveredId = hoveredNodeRef.current;
  if (hoveredId !== null) {
    const srcId = getLinkNodeId(link.source);
    const tgtId = getLinkNodeId(link.target);
    const isConnected = srcId === hoveredId || tgtId === hoveredId;
    if (!isConnected) continue;          // skip emission — link is dimmed
  }

  // … existing wave probability + emitParticle call unchanged …
}
```

This is a `ref` read inside a `rAF` callback, so no re-subscription is needed. The gate fires per frame.

#### Step 6 — Verify node emphasis is also view-mode-agnostic

Search for the `nodeColor` / `paintNode` path that handles the hovered node's brightness boost. Confirm it reads `hoveredNodeRef.current` (not `viewMode`). If it has a `viewMode` branch that short-circuits before applying the brightness boost, apply the same compose-last pattern. Based on the constants in the file, `getNodeColor` uses `getNodeSize`/`normalizedVal` and the brightness system — ensure the hover boost (`HOVER_BRIGHTNESS` or equivalent multiplier) is the last step regardless of which branch set the base color.

---

## How to Verify

```bash
# In Mesh:    hover node → connected links bold+glow, rest dim, particles on connected only ✓
# In Pathway: hover node → connected Terra/Lumen links bold+glow, rest dim, no particles ✓
# In Signal:  hover node → connected links bold+glow, rest dim, particles only on connected ✓
# Clear hover (move off canvas) → all links restore to resting state ✓
# Switch view mode while hovering → hover clears cleanly ✓
```

---

## Architectural Principle (so this doesn't drift)

**EAP-125 — View-mode early-return that swallows the shared interaction layer.**

> **Pattern:** A per-link (or per-node) callback dispatches on `viewMode` at the top using a chain of `if/return`. Each branch handles its view's resting appearance correctly — but because each branch returns, the shared interaction-layer code that follows the chain is unreachable. New view modes are added by copying the pattern; they inherit the escape-before-interaction bug silently. There is no test that catches it because the individual view renders fine in isolation.
>
> **Rule:** Inside any canvas draw callback, **view-mode selection and interaction-state composition must be separate, sequential steps:**
>
> ```
> Step 1: getLinkRestingColor(link, viewMode, …)   ← view knows nothing about hover
> Step 2: applyHoverEmphasis(restingColor, isConnected, hoveredId)  ← hover knows nothing about view
> ```
>
> The interaction layer is **always the last step**. It is never inside a `viewMode` branch. Any callback that early-returns per view must be refactored into a composable helper + a universal post-pass.
>
> **Structural enforcement:** Extract the resting-color logic into a pure helper function (`getLinkRestingColor`) that takes `viewMode` as an argument. The callback itself only calls that helper and then applies the universal hover transform. The pure helper is testable in isolation. The callback is never more than ~15 lines.

This is the structural rule. The separation of "what does this link look like at rest in this view?" from "is this link emphasized/dimmed right now?" is the same axis separation that the Signal view already uses correctly for `activeLinkSet` vs `previewLinkSet` — hover emphasis is simply a third, orthogonal dimension on the same model.

